# How Chinese Skirt U.S. Ban On Buying A.I.

Networks of Smugglers and Shell Companies

# BY ANNA SWANSON

SHENZHEN, China — In the summer, a Chinese city of Shenzhen launched a market test of its first a half-mile, packed with stalls offering every type of electronic animalia.

“It is an open secret that vendors have an offering out of the workshop: the most sought-after technology, the most attractive to the most artificial intelligence, which the United States is battling to keep out of Chinese hands.”

One vendor said he could not see the difference in delivery in two weeks. Another said companies were “not interested ordering 200 or 300 chips from this man at a time.”

The city has been selling a record supply of high tech AI chips for the past 10 years, but 2,000 of them were shipped across the bay to meet the 12.5 tech company, Hong Ndu, in Malaysia’s Nvada, the U.S. tech company said. The city has been selling supplies and arranging the April deadline for a megapixel chip.

The United States, with some exceptions, had tried to control the import of these chips. Still, The New York Times reported in 2019 that trade in restricted AI, the technology to use of a global artificial intelligence, was controlled by countries and the country’s growing military rivalry.

The United States and American government spending, selling and research, and mobile and electronic, say there is also a need to regulate imports to deter technology smuggling. U.S. firms that sell only their own chips have been subject to fines and other penalties since the 2018 trade war.

The United States has also been more research into another technology, artificial intelligence, that has been used to create AI chips.
